---
import { Picture } from "astro:assets"
import CaseStudy from "@/layouts/case-study.astro"
import { AspectRatio } from "@/components/ui/aspect-ratio"
import { getProject } from "@/data/projects"
import hourlyImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/hourly.png"
import specsImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/specs.png"
import weekImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/week.png"

const project = getProject("wheely-weather")!

const pictureFormats: ("avif" | "webp")[] = ["avif", "webp"]
const pictureWidths = [720, 1200]
const pictureSizes = "(min-width: 768px) 768px, 100vw"
---

<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="Wheely Weather"
  description="A cycling weather app that turns forecast data into a ride verdict, the best window to go, and the gear cues cyclists check before leaving."
  seoTitle="Wheely Weather · Cycling Weather Decision App"
  seoDescription="Wheely Weather is a cycling weather decision app that translates forecast data into ride-quality verdicts, hourly riding windows, and weather-based kit guidance."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Wheely Weather answers one near-term riding question: <em
      >is it worth going now?</em
    > General forecasts show the numbers, but they still leave cyclists to translate
    wind, rain, temperature, daylight, and air quality into a decision.
  </p>
  <p>
    I designed and built the product as a focused web app: verdict first,
    evidence close, and a useful next window when the current answer is no.
  </p>

  <h2>The Decision Moment</h2>
  <p>
    Before a ride, I was checking one weather app and falling back to another
    when the first came up short. The data was available, but the call was not.
    Six rider conversations confirmed the same pattern: feels-like temperature
    mattered more than the actual number, wind canceled more rides than rain,
    and one bad condition could override an otherwise decent forecast.
  </p>
  <p>
    That made the product brief narrow by design. The app had to work at a
    glance on a phone, state the recommendation clearly, and still show enough
    data for riders who wanted to check the call.
  </p>

  <h2>Product Direction</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Lead with a five-level ride rating: Great, Good, Fair, Poor, or Bad.
    </li>
    <li>
      Score the weakest riding signal instead of averaging bad conditions away.
    </li>
    <li>Name the limiting condition when the ride rating drops.</li>
    <li>
      Keep the raw weather signals visible for riders who disagree with the
      recommendation.
    </li>
    <li>
      Point to the next usable window before asking anyone to study a chart.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>System Design</h2>
  <p>
    The screen order follows the rider’s question sequence instead of the shape
    of a forecast API: can I go, why did it get that rating, what should I wear,
    and when does it improve?
  </p>

  <figure>
    <AspectRatio ratio={4 / 3}>
      <Picture
        src={specsImg}
        formats={pictureFormats}
        widths={pictureWidths}
        sizes={pictureSizes}
        alt="Ride Specs panel showing rain chance, feels-like temperature, wind, air quality, dewpoint, UV index, sunrise, and sunset."
      />
    </AspectRatio>
    <figcaption>
      Ride Specs keeps the forecast signals close to the verdict, so the
      recommendation stays explainable.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Riding Windows</h2>
  <p>
    A bad current rating should not end the session. The hourly view turns a
    “not now” into a specific window, while the week view highlights the day
    worth watching when today is not promising.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <AspectRatio ratio={4 / 3}>
      <Picture
        src={hourlyImg}
        formats={pictureFormats}
        widths={pictureWidths}
        sizes={pictureSizes}
        alt="Hour-by-hour Wheely Weather panel with a ride-quality chart and a plain-language note about a rain window."
      />
    </AspectRatio>
    <figcaption>
      The hourly view lets a “no right now” turn into a specific ride window.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <figure>
    <AspectRatio ratio={4 / 3}>
      <Picture
        src={weekImg}
        formats={pictureFormats}
        widths={pictureWidths}
        sizes={pictureSizes}
        alt="Eight-day forecast view titled “The Week’s Wheelies,” with the best riding day highlighted."
      />
    </AspectRatio>
    <figcaption>
      When today is not promising, the week view highlights the day worth
      watching.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Outcome</h2>
  <p>
    The shipped app replaced a scattered pre-ride check with one clear decision
    path: read the verdict, confirm the cause, and choose the next useful ride
    window. React, Vite, Tailwind CSS 4, Open-Meteo, OpenStreetMap/Nominatim,
    the NWS API, and Cloudflare Pages power the release.
  </p>
  <p>
    The strongest shift was moving weather from reference material to a
    recommendation. The next pass should capture where riders disagree with the
    verdict, then tune thresholds without turning a quick decision tool into a
    settings-heavy forecast app.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
